file_path <- "C:/Users/Minen/Downloads/mobiles_dataset.csv" 
df <- read.csv(file_path)

# 1. Convert Prices to USD

# Fix warnings
df[df == ""] <- NA  
df[df == "-"] <- NA  


exchange_rates <- list(
  PKR = 0.0036,  
  INR = 0.011,  
  CNY = 0.14,    
  AED = 0.27     
)

df$Price_USD_PKR <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.Pakistan.PKR) * exchange_rates$PKR)
df$Price_USD_INR <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.India.INR) * exchange_rates$INR)
df$Price_USD_CNY <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.China.CNY) * exchange_rates$CNY)
df$Price_USD_AED <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.Dubai.AED) * exchange_rates$AED)
df$Price_USD_Original <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.USA.USD))  

df$Avg_Price_USD <- rowMeans(df[, c("Price_USD_PKR", "Price_USD_INR", 
                                     "Price_USD_CNY", "Price_USD_AED", 
                                     "Price_USD_Original")], na.rm = TRUE)


# 2. Battery Capacity vs. Price Correlation

battery_price_correlation <- cor(df$Battery.Capacity.mAh, df$Avg_Price_USD, use = "complete.obs")

# Answer:
# The correlation coefficient is -0.042, meaning battery capacity has little to no effect on pricing.


# 3. RAM Size vs. Price Correlation

df$RAM_GB <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(gsub("GB", "", df$RAM))) 
ram_price_correlation <- cor(df$RAM_GB, df$Avg_Price_USD, use = "complete.obs")

# Answer:
# The correlation coefficient is 0.448, meaning higher RAM generally leads to higher smartphone prices.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

file_path <- "C:/Users/Minen/Downloads/mobiles_dataset.csv"  
df <- read.csv(file_path)

exchange_rates <- list(
  PKR = 0.0036,
  INR = 0.011,
  CNY = 0.14,
  AED = 0.27
)

df$Price_USD_PKR <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.Pakistan.PKR) * exchange_rates$PKR)
df$Price_USD_INR <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.India.INR) * exchange_rates$INR)
df$Price_USD_CNY <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.China.CNY) * exchange_rates$CNY)
df$Price_USD_AED <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.Dubai.AED) * exchange_rates$AED)
df$Price_USD_Original <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.USA.USD))

region_avg_prices <- colMeans(df[, c("Price_USD_PKR", "Price_USD_INR", 
                                     "Price_USD_CNY", "Price_USD_AED", 
                                     "Price_USD_Original")], na.rm = TRUE)

region_df <- data.frame(Region = names(region_avg_prices), Avg_Price = region_avg_prices)


# 1. Bar Chart: Average Price per Region

p1 <- ggplot(region_df, aes(x = Region, y = Avg_Price, fill = Region)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Average Smartphone Price per Region (USD)", x = "Region", y = "Average Price (USD)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))


print(p1)  

# 2. Pie Chart: Market Share of Smartphone Brands

brand_counts <- as.data.frame(table(df$Company.Name))
colnames(brand_counts) <- c("Brand", "Count")

p2 <- ggplot(brand_counts, aes(x = "", y = Count, fill = Brand)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  labs(title = "Market Share of Smartphone Brands") +
  theme_void()

print(p2)  

# 3. Save the Plots 

ggsave("avg_price_per_region.png", plot = p1, width = 7, height = 5, dpi = 300)
ggsave("brand_market_share.png", plot = p2, width = 7, height = 7, dpi = 300)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

file_path <- "C:/Users/Minen/Downloads/mobiles_dataset.csv"  
df <- read.csv(file_path)

df$Price_USD <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Launched.Price.USA.USD))
df$Battery_Capacity <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Battery.Capacity.mAh))
df$Screen_Size <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(df$Screen.Size.inches))


# 1. Boxplot: Price Distribution by Company in USA

p1 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = Company.Name, y = Price_USD, fill = Company.Name)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # Remove outliers from boxplots
  geom_jitter(aes(color = Company.Name), width = 0.2, alpha = 0.6) +  # Show data points
  scale_fill_manual(values = rainbow(length(unique(df$Company.Name)))) +
  scale_color_manual(values = rainbow(length(unique(df$Company.Name)))) +
  labs(title = "Price Distribution by Company in USA", 
       subtitle = "A boxplot showing how price varies by company with individual data points overlaid",
       x = "Company", y = "Price in USD") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

print(p1) 

# 2. Scatter Plot: Battery Capacity vs. Price in USA

p2 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = Battery_Capacity, y = Price_USD, color = Company.Name)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 3) +
  scale_color_manual(values = rainbow(length(unique(df$Company.Name)))) +
  labs(title = "Battery Capacity vs. Price in USA", 
       subtitle = "The relationship between battery capacity, price, and screen size across different smartphone brands",
       x = "Battery Capacity (mAh)", y = "Price (USD)") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p2)  

# 3. Scatter Plot for Top 5 Brands: Battery Capacity vs. Price

top_brands <- df %>%
  count(Company.Name, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(5, n) %>%
  pull(Company.Name)

df_top5 <- df %>% filter(Company.Name %in% top_brands)

brand_shapes <- c(16, 17, 18, 15, 3)  # Different shapes for different brands
names(brand_shapes) <- top_brands

p3 <- ggplot(df_top5, aes(x = Battery_Capacity, y = Price_USD, shape = Company.Name, color = Screen_Size)) +
  geom_point(size = 4, alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = brand_shapes) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red") +
  labs(title = "Battery Capacity vs. Price for Top 5 Brands",
       subtitle = "Different shapes for each brand, color by screen size (USA)",
       x = "Battery Capacity (mAh)", y = "Price (USD)") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p3)  

# 4. Save the Plots 

ggsave("price_distribution_boxplot.png", plot = p1, width = 10, height = 6, dpi = 300)
ggsave("battery_vs_price_scatter.png", plot = p2, width = 10, height = 6, dpi = 300)
ggsave("top5_brands_scatter.png", plot = p3, width = 10, height = 6, dpi = 300)

Part 4: Analysis & Conclusion

1. Boxplot Analysis: Price Distribution by Company in the USA

The boxplot visualization in Part 3 revealed significant price variations across smartphone brands. Apple, Google, and Samsung have the highest-priced models, with a wide range of price distribution. Brands like Xiaomi, Realme, and POCO primarily focus on budget-friendly devices, with much lower prices and fewer high-end models. Some brands, such as Sony and Huawei, have a mix of mid-range and premium devices, but their distributions show fewer budget models compared to Xiaomi or Realme.

Also Apples devices are consistently expensive, whereas brands like Xiaomi have significantly lower-priced models. Some brands have higher outliers, indicating a mix of premium models with a few low-cost ones.

2. Scatter Plot Analysis: Battery Capacity vs.Price in the USA

The scatter plot comparing battery capacity and price in the USA showed a weak correlation between the two. There are expensive phones with small batteries, such as Apple and Samsung devices, and budget phones with large batteries. Higher battery capacity does not necessarily mean a higher price. However, some ultra-premium phones have both a high price and a large battery.

We can see that budget phones tend to have larger batteries than some flagship models, indicating a focus on battery life in mid-range models.

3. Scatter Plot Analysis

The scatter plot for the top five brands, Apple, Honor, Oppo, Samsung, and Vivo, provided additional insights. Apples phones are the most expensive, even with lower battery capacities. Samsung has a mix of flagship and mid-range models, resulting in a spread across battery and price values. Oppo and Vivo devices tend to be mid-range, with higher battery capacities than Apple or Honor. Honor has some outlier models with large batteries and higher prices.

Therefore, Apple and Samsung dominate the premium price range. Oppo, Vivo, and Honor have strong representation in the mid-range segment.

4. Conclusion

Based on the visualizations and analysis, Apple, Google, and Samsung dominate the premium segment, whereas Xiaomi, POCO, and Realme focus on budget models. Battery capacity does not directly determine price, as some budget models have larger batteries than premium models. Screen size impacts price in some cases, but brand influence is a stronger factor in pricing. The top five brands show a clear segmentation, with Apple leading in price and Oppo and Vivo balancing battery and cost.

Final conclusion: Smartphone price is influenced more by brand and features than just battery capacity or screen size. Premium brands charge more regardless of battery capacity, whereas budget brands prioritize larger batteries for market competitiveness.
